answer:
The shortest path between two points is a straight line.  To minimize the total length of the ropes, the balloon should be positioned directly above the point $P$ on the ground such that $HP$ is perpendicular to $CD$.  This will create two right triangles, $\triangle HPD$ and $\triangle HPC$, with hypotenuses $HD$ and $HC$ respectively.

[asy]
size(250);
pair A, B, C, D, O, H, W, X, Y, Z;
O=(0,0);
A=(1,1);
D=(1.5,-.3);
B=(-1.5,.3);
C=(-1,-1);
H=(0,2.5);
W=(5/3)*(A+D);
X=(5/3)*(A+B);
Y=(-1)*(W);
Z=(-1)*(X);
draw(W--X--Y--Z--W);
draw(A--C);
draw(B--D);
draw(O--H, linewidth(1));
draw(A--H, dashed);
draw(B--H, dashed);
draw(C--H, dashed);
draw(D--H, dashed);
dot(A);
dot(B);
dot(C);
dot(D);
dot(O);
dot(H);
label("A", A, NE);
label("B", B, SW);
label("C", C, SE);
label("D", D, NE);
label("O", O, SE);
label("H", H, NW);
pair P;
P=(C+D)/2;
draw(H--P, dashed);
dot(P);
label("P", P, SE);
[/asy]

Let $x$ be the distance from $C$ to $P$.  Then the distance from $P$ to $D$ is $140-x$.  Using the Pythagorean Theorem in $\triangle HPC$ and $\triangle HPD$, we find that
$$HP^2 + x^2 = 150^2 \quad\text{and}\quad HP^2 + (140-x)^2 = 130^2.$$Expanding the second equation gives
$$HP^2 + 19600 - 280x + x^2 = 16900.$$Since $HP^2 + x^2 = 150^2 = 22500$, we can substitute to obtain
$$22500 + 19600 - 280x = 16900,$$which simplifies to $x = 108$.  Thus, the distance from $P$ to $D$ is $140-108 = 32$.

