draw(C--H, dashed);
draw(D--H, dashed);
dot(A);
dot(B);
dot(C);
dot(D);
dot(O);
dot(H);
label("A", A, NE);
label("B", B, SW);
label("C", C, SE);
label("D", D, NE);
label("O", O, SE);
label("H", H, NW);
pair P;
P=(C+D)/2;
draw(H--P, dashed);
dot(P);
label("P", P, SE);
draw(C--P, dashed);
draw(D--P, dashed);
label("$x$", (C+P)/2, W);
label("$140-x$", (D+P)/2, E);
[/asy]

The total length of the ropes is then
$$HA + HB + HC + HD = \sqrt{OA^2 + OH^2} + \sqrt{OB^2 + OH^2} + 150 + 130.$$Note that $OA = OB$ and $OH$ is constant, so the minimum of this expression occurs when $HA + HB$ is minimized.  By the Triangle Inequality,
$$\sqrt{OA^2 + OH^2} + \sqrt{OB^2 + OH^2} \ge \sqrt{(OA+OB)^2 + OH^2} = \sqrt{CD^2 + OH^2} = \sqrt{140^2 + OH^2}.$$Thus, the minimum total length of the ropes is
$$\sqrt{140^2 + OH^2} + 280.$$When $P$ is positioned as described above, the total length of the ropes is
$$HP + PD + PC + PD = \sqrt{HP^2 + x^2} + \sqrt{HP^2 + (140-x)^2} = 150 + 130 = 280.$$The greatest length of rope that can be saved is then $\boxed{20}$.

