The equations $y = ax + c$ and $y = ax + d$ intersect the $y$-axis at $(0, c)$ and $(0, d)$, respectively.  The distance between these points is $|c - d|$.  Similarly, the distance between the $y$-intercepts of the lines $y = bx + c$ and $y = bx + d$ is $|c - d|$.

[asy]
unitsize(1 cm);

pair trans;

real a, b, c, d;

a = 1;
b = 2;
c = -1;
d = 1;

trans = (10,0);

draw((-5,5*a + c)--(5,5*a + c),red);
draw((-5,5*a + d)--(5,5*a + d),red);
draw((-5,5*b + c)--(5,5*b + c),green);
draw((-5,5*b + d)--(5,5*b + d),green);
draw((-5,5*a + c + trans)--(5,5*a + c + trans),red);
draw((-5,5*a + d + trans)--(5,5*a + d + trans),red);
draw((-5,5*b + c + trans)--(5,5*b + c + trans),green);
draw((-5,5*b + d + trans)--(5,5*b + d + trans),green);

label("$y = ax + c$", (-5,5*a + c), SW, red);
label("$y = ax + d$", (-5,5*a + d), SW, red);
label("$y = bx + c$", (-5,5*b + c), SW, green);
label("$y = bx + d$", (-5,5*b + d), SW, green);
label("$y = ax + c$", (10,5*a + c + trans), SW, red);
label("$y = ax + d$", (10,5*a + d + trans), SW, red);
label("$y = bx + c$", (10,5*b + c + trans), SW, green);
label("$y = bx + d$", (10,5*b + d + trans), SW, green);
label("$y = bx - c$", (-5,-5*b - c), SE, blue);
label("$y = bx - d$", (-5,-5*b - d), SE, blue);
label("$y = ax - c$", (-5,-5*a - c), SE, red);
label("$y = ax - d$", (-5,-5*a - d), SE, red);
label("$y = ax - c$", (10,-5*a - c + trans), SE, red);
label("$y = ax - d$", (10,-5*a - d + trans), SE, red);
label("$y = bx - c$", (10,-5*b - c + trans), SE, blue);
label("$y = bx - d$", (10,-5*b - d + trans), SE, blue);

draw((-5,-5*a - c)--(5,-5*a - c),red);
draw((-5,-5*a - d)--(5,-5*a - d),red);
draw((-5,-5*b - c)--(5,-5*b - c),green);
draw((-5,-5*b - d)--(5,-5*b - d),green);
draw((-5,-5*a - c + trans)--(5,-5*a - c + trans),red);
draw((-5,-5*a - d + trans)--(5,-5*a - d + trans),red);
draw((-5,-5*b - c + trans)--(5,-5*b - c + trans),green);
draw((-5,-5*b - d + trans)--(5,-5*b - d + trans),green);

label("$y = ax - c$", (-5,-5*a - c), SE, red);
label("$y = ax - d$", (-5,-5*a - d), SE, red);
label("$y = bx - c$", (-5,-5*b - c), SE, green);
label("$y = bx - d$", (-5,-5*b - d), SE, green);
label("$y = ax - c$", (10,-5*a - c + trans), SE, red);
label("$y = ax - d$", (10,-5*a - d + trans), SE, red);
label("$y = bx - c$", (10,-5*b - c + trans), SE, green);
label("$y = bx - d$", (10,-5*b - d + trans), SE, green);
[/asy]

The area of a parallelogram is equal to the product of the lengths of its base and height.  The base of the parallelogram bounded by the lines $y = ax + c$, $y = ax + d$, $y = bx + c$, and $y = bx + d$ is $\frac{|c - d|}{|a|}$, and its height is $\frac{|b - a|}{|b|}$.  Thus, its area is $\frac{|c - d|}{|a|} \cdot \frac{|b - a|}{|b|}$.  Similarly, the area of the parallelogram bounded by the lines $y = ax + c$, $y = ax - d$, $y = bx + c$, and $y = bx - d$ is $\frac{|c - d|}{|a|} \cdot \frac{|b + a|}{|b|}$.

We are given that $\frac{|c - d|}{|a|} \cdot \frac{|b - a|}{|b|} = 18$ and $\frac{|c - d|}{|a|} \cdot \frac{|b + a|}{|b|} = 72$.  Dividing the second equation by the first, we get $\frac{|b + a|}{|b - a|} = 4$.  Thus, either $b + a = 4b - 4a$ or $b + a = -4b + 4a$.  The second equation yields $b = \frac{3a}{5}$, which is not an integer.  Thus, $b = 3a$.

Substituting $b = 3a$ into the first equation, we get $\frac{|c - d|}{|a|} \cdot \frac{|3a - a|}{|3a|} = 18$.  Thus, $|c - d| = 27a$.  The smallest possible values of $c$ and $d$ are $c = 1$ and $d = 28$, so the smallest possible value of $a + b + c + d$ is $1 + 3 + 1 + 28 = \boxed{33}$.

