answer:
Let $\theta = \angle BAC.$  Then $\angle ABC = \angle ACB = \frac{180^\circ - \theta}{2}.$  Also, since $\angle BDC = 3 \angle BAC,$ $\angle BDC = 3 \theta,$ and $\angle DBC = \angle DCB = 90^\circ - \theta.$

[asy]
unitsize(0.4 cm);

pair A, B, C, D, M;

A = (0,11);
D = (0,1);
B = (-11/2,0);
C = (11/2,0);
M = (B + C)/2;

draw(A--B--C--cycle);
draw(A--M);
draw(B--D--C);

label("$A$", A, N);
label("$B$", B, SW);
label("$C$", C, SE);
label("$D$", D, NW);
label("$M$", M, S);
[/asy]

Triangle $ABC$ is isosceles, so $BM = MC = \frac{BC}{2}.$  Also, $\angle DMB = \angle DMC = 90^\circ,$ so $DB = DC.$  Hence, triangles $BDM$ and $CDB$ are isosceles, so $\angle BMD = \angle BDM = 180^\circ - 2(90^\circ - \theta) = 2 \theta - 90^\circ$ and $\angle BDC = 180^\circ - 2(2 \theta - 90^\circ) = 6 \theta - 360^\circ.$

Since $\angle BDC = 3 \theta,$ $6 \theta - 360^\circ = 3 \theta,$ so $\theta = 120^\circ.$  Thus, $\angle ABC = \angle ACB = 30^\circ.$

Let $x = BC.$  Then, by the Law of Sines on triangle $ABC,$
$$\frac{AB}{\sin 30^\circ} = \frac{BC}{\sin 120^\circ}.$$Since $AB = AC,$ $AB = \frac{x \sin 30^\circ}{\sin 120^\circ} = \frac{x}{2 \sqrt{3}}.$  The perimeter of triangle $ABC$ is then
$$AB + AC + BC = \frac{3x}{2 \sqrt{3}} = \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} x.$$By the Pythagorean Theorem, $AM^2 + \left( \frac{1}{2} BC \right)^2 = AB^2,$ so
$$11^2 + \left( \frac{1}{2} x \right)^2 = \left( \frac{x}{2 \sqrt{3}} \right)^2.$$This simplifies to $x^2 = 880,$ so the perimeter is $\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} \cdot \sqrt{880} = \boxed{22 \sqrt{15}}.$

