Let $O$ be the center of the circle that passes through points $B$, $C$, $D$, and $M$.  Then $O$ lies on $\overline{AM}$, and $OD = OB = OC$.  Also, $\angle BOC = 2 \angle BAC = 2x$ and $\angle BOD = 2 \angle BDM = 4x$ and $\angle COD = 2 \angle CDM = 2x$.  Hence, $\angle BOC + \angle COD + \angle BOD = 8x = 360^\circ$, so $x = 45^\circ$.

[asy]
unitsize(0.4 cm);

pair A, B, C, D, M, O;

A = (0,11);
D = (0,1);
B = (-11/2,0);
C = (11/2,0);
M = (B + C)/2;
O = (0,11 - 2*sqrt(33));

draw(A--B--C--cycle);
draw(A--M);
draw(B--D--C);
draw(B--O--C);
draw(B--M--C);
draw(O--D);

label("$A$", A, N);
label("$B$", B, SW);
label("$C$", C, SE);
label("$D$", D, NW);
label("$M$", M, S);
label("$O$", O, NE);
[/asy]

Note that $\triangle BOC$ is isosceles, so $\angle OBC = \angle OCB = 45^\circ$.  Then $\angle BOM = 90^\circ$, so $\triangle BOM$ is a 45-45-90 triangle.  This means $OM = BM = \frac{11}{\sqrt{2}} = \frac{11\sqrt{2}}{2}$.  Similarly, $OM = CM = \frac{11\sqrt{2}}{2}$, so $BC = 11\sqrt{2}$.

Note that $\triangle BDM \sim \triangle BMA$, so $\frac{BD}{BM} = \frac{AD}{AM}$, or $\frac{BD}{\frac{11\sqrt{2}}{2}} = \frac{10}{11}$.  Hence, $BD = 5\sqrt{2}$.

Similarly, $\triangle CDM \sim \triangle CMA$, so $\frac{CD}{CM} = \frac{AD}{AM}$, or $\frac{CD}{\frac{11\sqrt{2}}{2}} = \frac{10}{11}$.  Hence, $CD = 5\sqrt{2}$.

Finally, the perimeter of $\triangle ABC$ is $AB + BC + CA = 2(AB) + BC$.  Since $\triangle ABD \sim \triangle AMB$, we have $\frac{AB}{AM} = \frac{BD}{BM}$, or $\frac{AB}{11} = \frac{5\sqrt{2}}{\frac{11\sqrt{2}}{2}} = \frac{10}{11}$.  Hence, $AB = 10$.  Thus, the perimeter of $\triangle ABC$ is $2(10) + 11\sqrt{2} = \boxed{20 + 11\sqrt{2}}$.

