answer:
The graph of $y = ax^2 + bx + c$ is a parabola. The values of $x^2,$ $x,$ and 1 at the endpoints of the interval $[0, 1]$ are shown below.

$$\begin{array}{c|ccc}
x & 0 & 1 & \\ \hline
x^2 & 0 & 1 & \text{The parabola is between these graphs.} \\
x & 0 & 1 & \\
1 & 1 & 1 &
\end{array}$$

Since $|ax^2 + bx + c| \le 1$ for all $x \in [0, 1],$ the entire parabola lies between the graphs of $y = 1$ and $y = -1.$

[asy]
import graph;
size(125);
Label f; 
f.p=fontsize(6);
xaxis(-0.5,6, Ticks(f, 1.0)); 
yaxis(-0.5,6, Ticks(f, 1.0)); //

real g(real x) 
{ 
return 1;
}
real h(real x) 
{ 
return -1;
}
real f(real x) 
{ 
return 81x^2-108x+35;
}
draw(graph(g,0,1), dashed);
draw(graph(h,0,1), dashed);
draw(graph(f,0,1));
label(" $y=1$", (1,1.2), E);
label(" $y=-1$", (1,-1.2), E);
[/asy]

The graph of $y = ax^2 + bx + c$ shown above is $y = 81x^2 - 108x + 35,$ whose coefficients sum to 1.  In this case, the vertex of the parabola occurs at $x = -\frac{b}{2a} = \frac{108}{162} = \frac{6}{9} = \frac{2}{3} \in [0, 1].$  So this parabola stays between $y = 1$ and $y = -1,$ and the sum of the coefficients is 1.

Any parabola with $|a| + |b| + |c|$ larger than 1 must have a vertex either to the left of 0 or to the right of 1.  In either case, we can find an $x$ in $[0, 1]$ such that either $ax^2 + bx + c > 1$ or $ax^2 + bx + c < -1,$ so the entire parabola does not lie between $y = 1$ and $y = -1.$

Thus, the largest possible value of $|a| + |b| + |c|$ is $\boxed{1}.$

Consider the polynomial $P(x) = ax^2 + bx + c.$  We are given that $|P(x)| \le 1$ for $0 \le x \le 1.$  Let
$$P_1(x) = 8x^2 - 8x + 1,$$$$P_2(x) = -8x^2 + 8x - 1.$$Then
$$|P_1(x)| \le 1$$for $0 \le x \le 1,$ and
$$|P_2(x)| \le 1$$for $0 \le x \le 1.$  (The graphs of $y = P_1(x)$ and $y = P_2(x)$ are shown below.)

[asy]
import graph;

real f(real x) { return 8x^2 - 8x + 1; }
real g(real x) { return -8x^2 + 8x - 1; }

path P1 = (0,1)--(1/2,1)--(1,1);
path P2 = (0,-1)--(1/2,-1)--(1,-1);

xaxis("$x$",EndArrow);
yaxis("$y$",EndArrow);

draw(graph(f,0,1),red);
draw(graph(g,0,1),blue);
draw(P1,red);
draw(P2,blue);
[/asy]

Let $P(x) = c_1 P_1(x) + c_2 P_2(x).$  Then
$$|c_1| |P_1(x)| + |c_2| |P_2(x)| \ge |P_1(x)|$$for $0 \le x \le 1,$ so
$$|c_1| + |c_2| \ge 1.$$Also,
$$P(0) = c_1,$$$$P(1) = c_2,$$so
$$|a| + |b| + |c| = |c_1 + c_2| + |2c_1 - c_2| \le 3(|c_1| + |c_2|) \le \boxed{3}.$$The maximum is achieved when $P(x) = P_1(x).$

