answer:
The line of reflection must be the perpendicular bisector of the segment connecting $\begin{pmatrix} 5 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix}$ and $\begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ 3 \end{pmatrix}.$  The midpoint of this segment is $\begin{pmatrix} \frac{9}{2} \\ \frac{3}{2} \end{pmatrix},$ and a possible equation for the line of reflection is $y = -x + c.$  Substituting the midpoint into this equation, we get $\frac{3}{2} = -\frac{9}{2} + c,$ so $c = 6.$  Hence, the line of reflection is $y = -x + 6.$

[asy]
size(150);
defaultpen(linewidth(0.8));
pair A = (5,0), B = (4,3), X = (2,5), M = (A+B)/2, P = (2,2), foot = (2,4);
real r = -1 + 2*2.5/5;
pair image = r*A + (1-r)*B;

draw((-1,7)--(-1,0),gray(0.7),Arrows(4));
draw((0,-1)--(8,0),gray(0.7),Arrows(4));
draw((-1,0)--(8,0));
draw((0,-1)--(0,7));

pair Y = (image.x,-image.y+6);

draw(A--B,EndArrow(4));
draw(A--image,EndArrow(4));
draw(B--image,EndArrow(4));
draw((2,2)--foot,EndArrow(4));
draw((2,2)--(2,0),EndArrow(4));
draw((2,0)--foot,EndArrow(4));
draw((0,0)--X,EndArrow(4));
draw((0,0)--foot,EndArrow(4));
draw((0,0)--Y,EndArrow(4));
draw((0,0)--(2,2),dashed,EndArrow(4));
draw((0,0)--foot,dashed,EndArrow(4));
draw((2,2)--foot,dashed,EndArrow(4));
draw((2,2)--(2,0),dashed,EndArrow(4));
draw((2,0)--foot,dashed,EndArrow(4));
draw((0,0)--(4,2),dashed,EndArrow(4));
draw((4,2)--foot,dashed,EndArrow(4));
draw((0,0)--(4,2)--image,dashed);
draw((4,2)--Y,dashed);

label("$x$", (8,0), E);
label("$y$", (0,7), N);
dot("$A = \begin{pmatrix} 5 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix}$", A, S);
dot("$B = \begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ 3 \end{pmatrix}$", B, NE);
dot("$X = \begin{pmatrix} -2 \\ 3 \end{pmatrix}$", X, NW);
dot(M);
dot(image);
dot(Y);
label("$y = -x + 6$", (4,-1), S);
[/asy]

To find the image of $\begin{pmatrix} -2 \\ 3 \end{pmatrix},$ we can use the line of reflection.  Upon reflection, the vector $\begin{pmatrix} -2 \\ 3 \end{pmatrix}$ is mapped to the vector $\begin{pmatrix} x \\ y \end{pmatrix}.$  The average of $\begin{pmatrix} -2 \\ 3 \end{pmatrix}$ and $\begin{pmatrix} x \\ y \end{pmatrix}$ is the foot of the perpendicular from the line, $\begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 4 \end{pmatrix}.$  Hence,
$$\begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 4 \end{pmatrix} = \frac{1}{2} \begin{pmatrix} -2 + x \\ 3 + y \end{pmatrix}.$$This gives us $x + (-2) = 4$ and $y + 3 = 8,$ so $\boxed{\begin{pmatrix} 6 \\ 5 \end{pmatrix}}.$

