question:
Rectangle $ABCD$ has center $O$ and $AB/AD=k$. A point is randomly chosen from the interior of rectangle $ABCD$. What is the probability that it is closer to $O$ than to any of the four vertices?  [asy]
size(200);
draw((-250,100)--(250,100)--(250,-100)--(-250,-100)--cycle);
dot((0,0));
label("$O$",(0,0),N);
label("$A$",(-250,100),NW); label("$B$",(250,100),NE); label("$C$",(250,-100),SE); label("$D$",(-250,-100),SW);[/asy]

answer:
Let $a=AB/2$ and $b=AD/2$.  The condition that a point is closer to $O$ than to $A$ is equivalent to its being in the half-plane determined by the perpendicular bisector $\ell$ of $\overline{OA}$.  The half-plane determined by $\ell$ that contains $A$ is where the point is closer to $A$ than to $O$, so the region where the point is closer to $O$ than to $A$ is the half-plane determined by $\ell$ that does not contain $A$.  This half-plane intersects two sides of the rectangle, forming the quadrilateral $WXYZ$ below.  [asy]
size(200);
pair A,B,C,D,O,W,X,Y,Z;
A=(0,5); B=(5,5); C=(5,0); D=(0,0);
O=(A+B+C+D)/4;
real k=1;
pair X,Y,Z;
X=foot(O,A,B);
Y=foot(O,B,C);
Z=foot(O,C,D);
W=2*X-A;
draw(W--X--Y--Z--cycle);
draw((-1.5,0)--(6,0));
draw((0,-1.5)--(0,6));
draw(A--B--C--D--cycle);
draw((-1.5,1)--(6,1));
draw((1,-1.5)--(1,6));
label("$\ell$",(0,1),W);
label("$A$",A,NE);
label("$B$",B,NE);
label("$C$",C,SE);
label("$D$",D,SW);
label("$O$",(O),SW);
label("$W$",W,NW);
label("$X$",X,N);
label("$Y$",Y,E);
label("$Z$",Z,S);
[/asy]$\triangle WXO \sim \triangle AOB$ because they share $\angle XOW$ and both have a right angle.  Therefore, $\frac{WX}{AB}= \frac{WO}{AO}$, so $WX = 2ab$.  Similarly, $YZ = 2ab$.  Also, $XY = a - WX = a - 2ab$ and $ZW = b - YZ = b - 2ab$.  Hence, \begin{align*}
[WXYZ] &= \frac{1}{2}(a - 2ab)(b - 2ab) + \frac{1}{2}(2ab)^2 \\
&= \frac{1}{2}(a^2 - 2a^2b + 4a^2b^2 + 4a^2b^2) \\
&= \frac{1}{2}(a^2 + 2a^2b + 8a^2b^2) \\
&= \frac{1}{2}a^2(1 + 2b + 8b^2).
\end{align*}By symmetry, the probability is just $\frac{[WXYZ]}{[ABCD]} = \frac{1 + 2b + 8b^2}{4b(1 + b)}$.  Substituting $b = \tfrac{k}{2}$, the probability is $\boxed{\frac{1 + k + 2k^2}{2k(1 + k)}}$.

